attributes.title: Assessing the Impact of Coronavirus Induced Anxiety on Cognitive Functions in an Online Learning Environment
attributes.description: Impact of Coronavirus related anxierty on  students who are transitioning to an online learning envrionment .  Project focuses on cognitve and non-cogntive variables.

copyright_holders: Morehouse Center for Excellence in Education

summary.value:
While innovation in education previously meant embracing creative and unorthodox instructional approaches, and addressing “disruptions” to the higher education context, few could have predicted a reality in which all educators would be forced to innovate at the same time, whether they were ready or not. As such, the COVID-19 pandemic has disrupted undergraduate education in unprecedented and comprehensive ways. College students have been asked to vacate campuses, return to their homes, and continue courses online until the end of the Spring 2020 semester impacting approximately 2,100 students. 
     University leaders recognize the resultant anxiety created in students because of COVID-19 social distancing expectations. However, the need to move courses online, knowing that the online learning experience in the patch quilt configuration will be suboptimal, this approach serves as a tradeoff given the need to keep people from congregating. Not yet apparent, however, are the implications this situational anxiety will have on student learning. Additionally, it is unclear whether students are returning to environments that will support their online academic and social-emotional needs during their separation from the college. The purpose of this research study is to discover whether there is a relationship between situational anxiety and noncognitive factors--psychological well-being, intent to persist, and perceptions of problem-solving abilities-- due to the abrupt transition from in-class learning to online and distance learning. Quasi-experimental survey-based research will be used to answer five research questions. Surveys will be administered to 200 students. Research findings will be used to inform policy, planning, and design of online and distance learning experiences. Student response data will be used to inform environmental conditions,  adjust pedagogical practices and improve user experience in distance learning environments. The study will be completed before the end of the Spring 2020 semester.

attributes.title: Emotions and Rejection
attributes.description:
This is the OSF project for an ongoing study by Dr. Gili Freedman and Dr. Justin Dainer-Best which asks questions about the role of mood and anxiety symptoms in beliefs about rejection. 

A pre-registration template has been uploaded as of March 20, 2019.

attributes.title: Bare metal stents versus drug-eluting stents in revascularization of unprotected left main coronary artery stenosis: a systematic review and meta-analysis with trial sequential analysis
attributes.description: Systematic review and meta-analysis with trial sequential analysis

q2.value: Drug-eluting stents are associated with different outcomes as compared to bare metal stents when used in percutaneous coronary intervention for treating unprotected left main coronary artery stenosis.

q3.value: Meta-Analysis - A systematic review of published studies.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: This is a systematic review and meta-analysis.

q8.value: Registration prior to any human observation of the data

q9.value: The data is to be curated from included studies into an Excel spreadsheet. The pooled effects are unknown until formal analysis.

question.value:
PubMed, EMBASE, MEDLINE and Scopus will be searched electronically up to March 2020. No restriction is placed on language or publication period. ClinicalTrials.gov is also searched electronically up to April 2020 to identify any ongoing study. Reference lists of relevant identified literature will be manually searched to identify further relevant citations eligible for inclusion.
Studies reporting clinical outcomes which compared bare metal stent and drug-eluting stents for use in treating unprotected left main coronary artery stenosis. A minimum of 5 patients were required. Single-arm studies, and mechanistic studies that did not report clinical outcomes were excluded. Case reports, reviews, meta-analyses, and any conference publication (including but not limited to abstracts, papers, and posters) are excluded. Wherever overlapping of patient populations is likely, data from the most updated trial is included. Multiple studies reporting clinical trials under the same name or trial registry number are considered to pertain to the same trial.
Data will be manually extracted from published manuscripts and supplementary materials by 2 independent reviewers from a pool of 6. Authors of included studies will be contacted for information if necessary. Any discrepency will be resolved by an independent reviewer. Data will be entered into an electronic Excel spreadsheet data collection form. Continuous variables will be collected as mean and standard deviations. Dichotomous variables will be collected as event counts.

q11.value: There is no set sample size for meta-analyses.

question.value:
Primary outcomes are all-cause mortality, cardiovascular mortality, re-intervention, and myocardial infarction. All outcomes are to be recorded at 30 days, 1 year, 3 years, and 5 years.
Secondary outcomes include:
at 30 days: requirement of pacemaker, access site complications;
at 30 days and 1 year: stroke, new onset arrhythmia, BARC-defined major bleeding (classes IIIB-V), requirement of implantable cardioverter defibrillator; and
at 30 days, 1 year, 3 years, and 5 years: in-stent thrombosis, and ischaemic cardiomyopathy or new onset heart failure.
If in-hospital event counts were reported but 30-day counts were not, in-hospital event counts are used in place of 30-day counts.

Basic data to be extracted include the title, first author's surname, sample sizes, and year of publication of included studies.
Baseline characteristics of included patients to be extracted include age, sex, diabetes mellitus, hypertension, chronic kidney disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, peripheral arterial disease, heart failure, atrial fibrillation, pacemaker usage, implantable cardioverter defibrillator usage, valvular heart disease, previous stroke, previous myocardial infarction, previous coronary artery bypass graft, previous cardiac surgery, previous percutaneous coronary intervention, left ventricular ejection fraction, Society of Thoracic Surgeons (STS) score, EuroSCORE, EuroSCORE II, anticoagulant usage, and anti-platelet usage.
Procedural characteristics of included patients to be extracted include concomitant non-left main percutaneous coronary intervention, concomitant cardiac intervention(s), total number of stents placed, number of stens placed in left main coronary artery, number of different types of drug-eluting stents (including but not limited to sirolimus, everolimus and paclitaxel-eluting stents), number of patients with bifurcation stenting, use of radial access, use of femoral access, and use of vascular closure device.

Meta-analytical models will be used. Discrete variables are pooled using the Mantel–Haenszel method with risk ratios as the effect measure. Continuous variables are pooled using the inverse variance method with weighed mean difference as the effect measure. DerSimonian-Laird random effects model will be used. Relative risks will be used as the principle effect summary statistic.
Heterogeneity is assessed by the Cochran's Q test and I² statistic. The latter value exceeding 0.40 will be considered to signify significant heterogeneity. For variables reported by at least 10 studies, publication bias is assessed visually by funnel plot and quantitatively by Egger's test.
Trial sequential analysis will also be performed on all primary outcomes using a combination of sample size and effect size. The Z score threshold will be adjusted using the O’Brien-Fleming α-spending function. Studies reporting 0 events are to be handled by adding a constant (1) to both arms. Required information size will be estimated from studies with low risk of bias. Incidences are calculated from studies with low risk of bias. A pre-specified permissible two-sided type 1 error of 5% and type 2 error of 20% will be used.
All p values are two-sided, and values less than 0.05 are considered to be statistically significant. The meta-analytical component is to be performed using Review Manager version 5.3.5 (Copenhagen: The Nordic Cochrane Centre, The Cochrane Collaboration, 2014) and/or Comprehensive Meta-Analysis version 3 (Biostat, Englewood, United States of America). The trial sequential analysis component is to be performed using the Copenhagen trial unit, TSA software version 0.9.5.10 Beta.

q22.value:
Risk of bias assessment will be carried out using tools stipulated in the Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions. Randomized controlled trials will be assessed using the ROB-2 tool while observational studies will be assessed using the ROBINS-1 tool. Each study will be assessed by 2 independent reviewers of a pool of 6. Any discrepency will be resolved by an independent reviewer.
Subgroup analysis of data from studies deemed to have low risk of bias, and one of data from randomized controlled trials will be performed to serve as sensitivity analysis. Additionally, data froms studies performed in 2010 or later will be pooled, in view of the last meta-analysis on this subject having been published in 2010. This subgroup analysis also gives more contemporary and thus clinically relevant data.

attributes.title: The "Food Studies" Corpus
attributes.description:
This dataset is part of a study that used scoping review methodology to collect and verify the applicability of the phrase "Food Studies" in bibliographic records across five databases. Five large bibliographic databases were identified for size, relevance to food studies, and subject metadata standards. These were ProQuest Central (PQC), EBSCO Discovery Service (EDS), Web Of Science (WOS), PubMed (PM), and PubAg. The phrase “food studies” was then searched within each database, using a scholarly or peer-reviewed filter. The date range for the articles was all-time, through the date of the final search (December 3, 2019.) 

Each database’s search results were exported, transferred, and pooled into bibliographic management software (EndNote). Using endnote, the author verified “food studies” in the metadata, and prepared the metadata for screening. (No deduplication methods were used in this or the next phase because metadata can differ between duplicates.) Eligibility criteria for results were determined to be any peer-reviewed article’s record that contained data in its keyword, index term, subject, or heading fields, and had the phrase “food studies” anywhere in its metadata. 

The results were then imported into ES management software (Covidence), where all records were screened for relevance or irrelevance. Two major exclusion parameters were used in this phase. The first was whether the phrase “food studies” was lexically written as a plural or uncountable noun. Secondarily, I conducted background research for unfamiliar uses of “food studies” as a concept.

Once completed, this set of citations constituted The “Food Studies” Corpus. Because keyword frequency results rely on counting exact textual strings from five different database sources, the keywords needed to be crosswalked, or clustered and merged. Textual differences were cleaned through algorithmic clustering.The corpus was prepared and exported into a tabular document. This tabbed-corpus was then imported into data cleaning software (OpenRefine). OpenRefine contains several clustering methods. The number of keywords and clusters for each method, used in succession, can be found in "Keyword Clustering" spreadsheet. (Note that each text cluster was manually evaluated before merging—no merge was automatic.)
